tern Inner-Worldly Mysticism in the Modern West -- tAleister Crowley, Sexual Magick, and Drugs: Some Ambiguities of Sex, Will, and Power in Inner-Worldly Mysticism -- tFeminist Spirituality: The Return of Sophia -- tTranspersonal Psychology, New Age Spirituality, and the Human Sciences -- tConcluding Reflections -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLives in Spirit explores the dynamic conflicts that both energized and distorted the spiritual development of key precursor figures of a contemporary secular or "this-worldly" mysticism. With its historical roots in the early Gnostics and Plotinus, this characteristically Western spirituality re-emerges with the secularization and loss of traditional religious belief of modernity. The lives, works, and direct experiences of Nietzsche, Emerson, Thoreau, Jung, Heidegger, Gurdjieff, Crowley, and contemporary feminist mysticism are considered in terms of transpersonal psychology (Almaas), the sociology of mysticism (Weber and Troeltsch), and contemporary psychoanalysis (Winnicott, Bion, Kohut). Spiritual or essential experience is seen as an inherent form of human intelligence, which while potentially and even increasingly impacted by personal dynamics and social crisis, is not reducible to them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMysticismxCase studiesxPsychology. 0aMysticismxPsychologyvCase studies. 0aMysticismxPsychology. 0aSecularismxCase studiesxPsychology. 0aSecularismxPsychologyvCase studies. 0aSecularismxPsychology. 0aSpiritualityxCase studiesxPsychology. 0aSpiritualityxPsychologyvCase studies. 0aSpiritualityxPsychology. 0aTranspersonal psychologyvCase studies. 0aTranspersonal psychologyxCase studies. 0aTranspersonal psycholo